image.asymptote:
// 3-D interactive (WebGL) figure.
import graph3; size(10cm); currentprojection=orthographic(5,2.3,2.6);
real f(pair p){return 1.6+0.35*sin(1.1*p.x)-0.12*(p.y-1.5)^2;}
real L=3;
draw(surface((0,0,0)--(L,0,0)--(L,L,0)--(0,L,0)--cycle), gray(0.85)+opacity(0.6));
for(int i=0;i<=3;++i){ draw((i,0,0)--(i,L,0), gray(0.5)+0.3pt); draw((0,i,0)--(L,i,0), gray(0.5)+0.3pt); }
label("parameter domain $(u,v)$", (L/2,L+0.4,0), gray(0.3));
surface s=surface(f,(0,0),(L,L),28,28);
draw(s, rgb(0.6,0.78,0.95)+opacity(0.5));
for(int i=0;i<=3;++i){
  path3 uc=graph(new triple(real u){return (u,i,f((u,i)));},0,L,40,operator ..); draw(uc, blue+0.7pt);
  path3 vc=graph(new triple(real v){return (i,v,f((i,v)));},0,L,40,operator ..); draw(vc, red+0.7pt);
}
label("surface $S$", (L/2,L+0.4,f((L/2,L))+0.2));
draw((L/2,L/2,0.08)--(L/2,L/2,f((L/2,L/2))-0.12), black+1pt, Arrow3);
label("$T$", (L/2,L/2,f((L/2,L/2))/2), 2E);
draw(O--(L+0.7,0,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,L+0.9,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,0,2.4),gray,Arrow3);
label("$x$",(L+0.7,0,0),S); label("$y$",(0,L+0.9,0),E); label("$z$",(0,0,2.4),N);

statement.p:
It is called regular at (u,v) if
\boxed{ \mathbf r_u(u,v)\times \mathbf r_v(u,v)\ne \mathbf 0. }
A smooth regular parametrization gives a smooth surface patch.

subsection.p:
A graph z=g(x,y) is a surface. It has the natural parametrization \boxed{ \mathbf r(x,y)=(x,y,g(x,y)). } The two tangent vectors are \mathbf r_x=(1,0,g_x), \qquad \mathbf r_y=(0,1,g_y). Their cross product is
\mathbf r_x\times \mathbf r_y \amp= (-g_x,-g_y,1).
So a normal vector to the graph is \boxed{ (-g_x,-g_y,1). }
